    <section class="key-concepts" id="sect-00010">
    <title>Key Concepts</title>
    <list id="list-00011">
    <item>Logical connectives are used to form compound logical statements by using words such as and, or, and if … then.</item>
    <item>A disjunction joins two logical statements with the “or” connective. In, logic ‘or’ is inclusive. For a or statement to be true at least one statement must be true, but both may also be true.</item>
    <item>A conditional statement has the form if p, then q, where p and q are logical statements. The only time the conditional statement is false is when p is true, and q is false.</item>
    <item>A conditional statement has the form if p, then q, where p and q are logical statements. The only time the conditional statement is false is when p is true, and q is false.</item>
    <item>The biconditional statement is formed using the connective “if and only if” for the biconditional statement to be true, the true values of p and q, must match. If p is true then q must be true, if p is false, then q must be false.</item>
    <item>Translate compound statements between words and symbolic form.
     <table summary="." id="table-00002">
       <tgroup cols="3">
       <colspec colnum="1" colname="c1" colwidth="1*"/>
       <colspec colnum="2" colname="c2" colwidth="1*"/>
